 (Up to 2012)\n| publisher = India Meteorological Department\n| date = December 2016\n| page = M200\n| accessdate = 29 March 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n\n\n{{Panorama\n|image      = File:TirunelveliPanorama.jpg\n|caption    = Panoramic view of Tirunelveli as viewed from the Palayamkottai bank of river [[Thamirabarani]]. Sulochana Mudaliar bridge, the 12-arch link between both cities, is on the far right of this Deepavali 2009 image.\n|alt=a panoramic view of a river and the city skyline in the harbour\n|height     = 200\n}}\n\n==Demographics==\n{{bar box|title=Religious census|titlebar=#ddd|left1=Religion|right1=Percent(%)|float=left|bars={{bar percent|[[Hinduism|Hindu]]|Orange|69.00}}{{bar percent|[[Islam|Muslim]]|Green|20.02}}{{bar percent|[[Christianity|Christian]]|purple|10.59}}{{bar percent|[[Jainism|Jain]]|Blue|0.02}}{{bar percent|[[Sikhism|Sikh]]|yellow|0.01}}{{bar percent|[[Buddhism|Buddhist]]|Gold|0.01}}{{bar percent|Other|grey|0.35}}}}\n\nAccording to [[2011 census of India|2011 census]], Tirunelveli had a population of 473,637 with a sex-ratio of 1,027 females for every 1,000 males, much above the national average of 929.{{sfn|Census dashboard|2011}} A total of 46,624 were under the age of six, constituting 23,894 males and 22,730 females. [[Scheduled Castes and Scheduled Tribes]] accounted for 13.17% and .32% of the population respectively. The average literacy of the city was 81.49%, compared to the national average of 72.99%.{{sfn|Census dashboard|2011}} The city had a total of 120,466 households. There were a total of 182,471 workers, comprising 2,088 cultivators, 5,515 main agricultural labourers, 18,914 in house hold industries, 142,435 other workers, 13,519 marginal workers, 166 marginal cultivators, 913 marginal agricultural labourers, 1,828 marginal workers in household industries and 10,612 other marginal workers.{{sfn|Census of India|2011}}\n\nAccording to provisional data from the 2011 census the Tirunelveli urban agglomeration had a population of 498,984, with 246,710 males and 252,274 females. The overall [[human sex ratio|sex ratio]] in the city was 1023, and the [[child sex ratio]] was 957. Tirunelveli had a literacy rate of 91 percent, with male literacy 95 percent and female literacy 87 percent. A total of 42,756 of the city's population was under age six.{{sfn|Provisional population totals of 2011}}\n\nAs per the religious census of 2011, Tirunelveli had 69.0% [[Hindus]], 20.02% [[Muslims]], 10.59% [[Christians]], 0.01% [[Sikhs]], 0.01% [[Buddhists]], 0.02% [[Jainism|Jains]] and 0.35% following other religions.{{sfn|Religious census|2011}}\n\nThe city covers an area of {{convert|108.65|sqkm|sqmi}}. The population density of the city in the 2001 census was 3,781 persons per square kilometre, compared with 2,218 persons per square kilometre in 1971. Hindus form the majority of the urban population, followed by Muslims and Christians. Tamil is the main language spoken in the city, but the use of English is relatively common; English is the medium of instruction in most educational institutions and offices in the service sector. The Tamil dialect spoken in this region is distinct, and is widely spoken throughout Tamil Nadu.{{sfn|About the city}}{{sfn|Census of India|2001}}\n\n==Economy==\nInscriptions from the eighth to the 14th centuries (during the rule of the Pandyas, Cholas and later Tenkasi Pandyas) indicate the growth of Tirunelveli as a centre of economic growth which developed around the Nellaiappar temple. The drier parts of the province also flourished during the rule of the Vijayanagara kings. From 1550 until the early modern era, migration to the city from other parts of the state was common and the urban regions became hubs of manufacturing and commerce. Tirunelveli was a strategic point, connecting the eastern and western parts of the peninsula, as well as a trading centre. Records of sea and overland trade between 1700 and 1850 indicate close trading connections with [[Sri Lanka]] and [[Kerala]].{{sfn|Kumar|2003|pp=113\u2013115}} During the 1840s, cotton produced in the region was in demand for British mills.{{sfn|Kumar|2003|pp=112}} The chief exports during British rule were cotton, [[jaggery]], chillies, tobacco, palmyra fibre, salt, dried saltwater fish and cattle.{{sfn|Hunter|1908|p=372}}\n\nOccupations in Tirunelveli include service-sector activities such as administration, agricultural trading, tourism, banking, agro-machinery, cement manufacturing, information technology and educational services.{{sfn|Kanmony|2010|p=42}} In 1991, the Tirunelveli region ranked second in the number of women workers.{{sfn| Kapadia|2002|p=74}} Service sectors such as tourism have developed, due to a growth in religious tourism. Tirunelveli has [[beedi]] and cement factories, tobacco companies, workshops for steel-based products and mills for cotton textiles, spinning and weaving; there are also small-scale industries, such as tanneries and brick kilns. The agricultural areas, hand-woven clothes and household industries contribute to the economic growth of the city.{{sfn|Urban Infrastructure report|2007|p=15}} Food-processing industries have developed since the late 1990s; at the district level, it is the foremost industria l segment.{{sfn|Soundarapandian|2002| p=49}} Industries involving rice-making, blue-jelly metal manufacturing and jem power generating are located on the outskirts of the city.{{sfn|Soundarapandian|2002| pp=52\u201353}} The major agricultural produce in the region is [[Paddy field|paddy]] and cotton.{{sfn| Ramchandani|2000|p=144}} Beedi production during the 1990s earned an annual revenue of {{INR}}190&nbsp;billion and a foreign exchange of {{INR}}8&nbsp;billion across the three districts of Tirunelveli, Tiruchirapalli and Vellore.{{sfn|Soundarapandian|2002| p= 160}}\n\nTirunelveli is a major area for wind-power generation. Most wind-power-generation units in Tamil Nadu are located in Tirunelveli and Kanyakumari Districts. In 2005 they contributed 2036.9 MW to the state power-generation capacity. Many private, multinational wind companies are located on the outskirts of the city.{{sfn|''The Economic Times''|26 July 2012}} In June 2007 the [[Tata Group]] signed a [[memorandum of understanding]] with the state government to open a [[titanium dioxide]] plant, with an estimated value of {{INR}}25&nbsp;billion, in [[Tirunelveli district|Tirunelveli District]] and [[Thoothukudi District]]. However, the state government put the project on hold after increasing protests against it.{{sfn|''The Indian Express''|31 July 2007}}\n\nTirunelveli has two Special Economic Zones in the outskirts of the city, one located in Gangaikondan in the North along NH 44 and another one located in Nanguneri in South along NH 44. They house some of MNCs such as Atos Syntel, Coca Cola, Yokohama Rubber Company, Indian Oil Corporation Limited, Novo Carbon Private Limited, Bosch Limited, Alliance Tyre Group, Ramco Cements, India Cements, etc.\n\n=={{anchor|Municipal administration and politics}}Administration and politics==\n{| class=\"toccolours\" style=\"clear:right; float:right; background:#fff; margin:0 0 0.5em 1em; width:280px;\" font-size : \"90%\"\n|-\n!  style=\"background:#a8bdec; text-align:center;\" colspan=\"2\"|'''Municipal officials'''\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| Chairman||vacant{{sfn|Tirunelveli Municipality chairman|2011}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|Commissioner||Ajay Yadav{{sfn|Tirunelveli Municipality Commissioner|2011}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|Police Commissioner||Deepak M Damor, IPS{{sfn|Tirunelveli Municipality vice-chairman|2011}}\n|-\n!  style=\"background:#a8bdec; text-align:center;\" colspan=\"2\"|'''Elected members'''\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|Member of Legislative Assembly||Lakshmanan{{sfn|MLA of Tirunelveli|2011}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|Member of Parliament||[[gnanadhiraviyam from DMK]]{{sfn|MP of Tirunelveli|2019}}\n|}\nThe Tirunelveli Municipality was established in 1866 during British rule.{{sfn|Hunter|1908|pp=379\u2013380}} It became a City Municipal Corporation in 1994, bringing the [[Palayamkottai]] and Melapalayam municipalities, the Thatchanallur town panchayat and eleven other village panchayats within the city limits. The municipal corporation has five zones: Tirunelveli, Thatchanallur, Palayamkottai, Pettai and Melapalayam. The corporation has 55 wards, with an elected councillor for each ward.{{sfn|Urban Infrastructure report|2007|p=15}}{{sfn|About Corporation|2011}} The corporation has six departments: general administration and personnel, engineering, revenue, public health, city planning and information technology (IT).{{sfn|Commissionerate of Municipal Administration|2006}} All departments are under the control of a municipal commissioner.{{sfn|Commissionerate of Municipal Administration|2006}} Legislative power is vested in a body of 55 members, one from each ward.{{sfn|List of Councillors|2011}} The legislative body is headed by an elected chairperson, assisted by a deputy.{{sfn|Economic and political weekly|1995}} Tirunelveli city is district headquarters for the Tirunelveli district.\n\nThe city is part of the [[Tirunelveli (State Assembly Constituency)|Tirunelveli assembly]] constituency, electing a member to the [[Tamil Nadu Legislative Assembly]] every five years.{{sfn|List of Assembly constituencies|2010}} Since the 1977 elections, the assembly seat was held by the [[Dravida Munnetra Kazhagam]] (DMK) for three terms (following the 1989, 1996 and 2006 elections and the [[ADMK|All India Anna Dravid Munnetra Kazhagam]] (AIADMK) for six terms following the 1977, 1980, 1984, 1991, 2001 and 2011 elections.{{sfn|Partywise Comparison Since 1977|2011}} The current [[Member of the Legislative Assembly (India)|MLA]] is Nainar Nagendran, ex-minister and a leader of AIADMK.{{sfn|MLA of Tirunelveli|2011}}\n\nTirunelveli is a part of the [[Tirunelveli (Lok Sabha constituency)|Tirunelveli Lok Sabha constituency]], with ten assembly constituencies: Tirunelveli, [[Vasudevanallur (State Assembly Constituency)|Vasudevanallur (SC)]], [[Sankaranayanarkoil (State Assembly Constituency)|Sankarankoil (SC)]], Kadayanallur, [[Nanguneri (State Assembly Constituency)|Nanguneri]], [[Ambasamudram (State Assembly Constituency)|Ambasamudram]], [[Tenkasi (State Assembly Constituency)|Tenkasi]], [[Alangulam (State Assembly Constituency)|Alangulam]], [[Radhapuram (State Assembly Constituency)|Radhapuram]] and [[Palayamkottai (State Assembly Constituency)|Palayamkottai]].{{sfn|Parliamentary constituency map|2008}} The current Member of Parliament from the constituency is K.R.P. Prabakaran of the [[All India Anna Dravida Munnetra Kazhagam|AIADMK]].{{sfn|MP of Tirunelveli|2014}} Since 1957, the Tirunelveli parliament seat was held by the [[Indian National Congress]] for four terms: 1957\u20131961,{{sfn|Key highlights of the general elections 1957 to the Second Lok Sabha}} 1962\u201367,{{sfn|Key highlights of the general elections 1962 to the Third Lok Sabha}} 2004\u201309{{sfn|Key highlights of the general elections 2004 to the Fourteenth Lok Sabha}} and 2009-14. The Swantantra Party and the [[Communist Party of India|CPI]] won once each, from 1967\u201371 {{sfn|Key highlights of the general elections 1967 to the Fourth Lok Sabha}} and 1971\u201377 respectively.{{sfn|Key highlights of the general elections 1971 to the Fifth Lok Sabha}} The DMK won the seat twice: 1980\u201384{{sfn|Key highlights of the general elections 1980 to the Seventh Lok Sabha}} and 1996\u201398.{{sfn|Key highlights of the general elections 1996 to the Eleventh Lok Sabha}} The ADMK won the seat seven times: 1977\u201380,{{sfn|Key highlights of the general elections 1977 to the Sixth Lok Sabha}} 1984\u201389,{{sfn|Key highlights of the general elections 1984 to the Eighth Lok Sabha|publisher=Election Commission of India}} 1989\u201391,{{sfn|Key highlights of the general elections 1989 to the Ninth Lok Sabha}} 1991\u201396,{{sfn|Key highlights of the general elections 1991 to the Tenth Lok Sabha}} 1998,{{sfn|Key highlights of the general elections 1998 to the Twelfth Lok Sabha}} 1999\u20132004{{sfn|Key highlights of the general elections 1999 to the Thirteenth Lok Sabha}} and 2014 elections.{{sfn|MP of Tirunelveli|2014}}\n\nOrder in the city is maintained by the Tirunelveli City division of the [[Tamil Nadu Police]], headed by a commissioner.{{sfn|Tirunelveli district police|2011}} There are units for prohibition enforcement, district crime, social justice and human rights, district crime records and a special branch operating at the district level, each headed by a deputy superintendent of police.{{sfn|Tirunelveli district police|2011}}\n\n==Transport==\n{{Main article|Transport in Tirunelveli}}\n[[File:Tirunelveli Junction.JPG|Tirunelveli railway junction|thumb|left|alt=entrance of a railway station]]\nTirunelveli has an extensive transport network and is well-connected to other major cities by road, rail and air. The corporation maintains a total of {{convert|763.3|km|mi|abbr=on}} of roads. The city has {{convert|134.88|km|mi|abbr=on}} of concrete roads, {{convert|375.51|km|mi|abbr=on}} of BT roads,<!--What is this?--> {{convert|94.291|km|mi|abbr=on}} of water-bound macadam roads, {{convert|76.31|km|mi|abbr=on}} of unpaved roads and {{convert|82.3|km|mi|abbr=on}} of highways. Twenty-two kilometres (fourteen miles) of highway are maintained by the State Highways Department and thirty kilometres (nineteen miles) by the National Highways Department.{{sfn|Urban Infrastructure report|2007|p=19}} In 1844 a bridge was built by Colonel Horsley across the Tamirabarani River, connecting Tirunelveli to Palayamkottai.{{sfn|Caldwell|1989|p=89}} The city is located on [[National Highway 7 (India)(old numbering)|NH 7]], {{convert|150|km|mi|abbr=on}} south of [[Madurai]] and {{convert|91|km|mi|abbr=on}} north of [[Kanyakumari]]. NH 7A, an extension of NH 7, connects Palayamkottai with Tuticorin Port. Tirunelveli is also connected by major highways to [[Kollam]], [[Tiruchendur]], [[Rajapalayam]], [[Sankarankovil]], [[Ambasamudram]] and [[Nazareth]].{{sfn|About the city}}\n\nThe main bus stand (popularly known as the New Bus Stand), opened in 2003, is located in Veinthaankulam and there is regular bus service to and from the city. Other bus stands (for intracity service) are the Junction and Palay bus stands.{{sfn|About the city}} The [[Tamil Nadu State Transport Corporation]] has daily service to a number of cities, and the corporation operates a computerised reservation centre in the main bus stand.{{sfn|SETC Computer reservation centres|2004}} It also operates local buses serving the city and neighbouring villages. The Periyar bus stand commonly known as the old bus stand is fully demolished and a new bus station will be built under smart city plan The [[State Express Transport Corporation (Tamil Nadu)|State Express Transport Corporation]] has intercity service to [[Bangalore]], [[Chennai]], [[Kanyakumari]], [[Trivandrum]] and other cities.{{sfn|About the city}\n\n[[Tirunelveli Junction railway station]] is one of the oldest railway stations in India. The line from Tirunelveli to Sengottai was opened in 1903; the connection to [[Kollam Junction railway station|Quilon]], which was completed later, was the most important trade route to Travancore province in British India.{{sfn|Hunter|1908|pp=373}} The city is connected to major cities in all four directions: Madurai and Sankarankovil to the north, [[Nagercoil]] and [[Trivandrum]] to the south, Sengottai and [[Kollam]] to the west and Tiruchendur to the east. Tirunelveli is also connected to major Indian cities with daily service to [[Chennai]], [[Coimbatore]], [[Tiruchirappalli]], [[Madurai]], [[Salem, Tamil Nadu|Salem]], [[Ernakulam]], [[Trivandrum]], [[Mumbai]], [[Guruvayur]], [[Howrah]], [[Delhi]],[[Kollam]], [[Palghat]] and [[Ahmedabad]]. There is daily passenger service to [[Madurai]], [[Tiruchendur]], [[Tiruchirapalli]], [[Mayiladuthurai]], [[Palghat]] and [[Kollam]].{{sfn|Trains to Tirunelveli}}\n\nThe nearest airport to Tirunelveli is [[Tuticorin Airport]] (TCR) at Vaagaikulam in [[Thoothukkudi]] District, {{convert|22|km|mi|abbr=on}} east of the city, which offers daily flights to Chennai. The nearest international airports are [[Madurai Airport|Madurai International Airport]], {{convert|150|km|mi|abbr=on}} away and [[Thiruvananthapuram International Airport]] (TRV), about {{convert|130|km|mi|abbr=on}} away.{{sfn|About the city}}\n\n==Culture==\n{{see also|Temples of Tirunelveli}}\n[[Nellaiappar Temple]] is a Hindu temple dedicated to [[Shiva]] in the form of Nellaiappar. The deity is revered in the verses of ''[[Tevaram]]'', a seventh-century Saiva work by [[Sambandar]]. The temple was greatly expanded during the 16th-century Nayak period and has a number of architectural attractions, including musical pillars.{{sfn|Soundara Rajan| 2001| p= 63}} The temple has several festivals, the foremost an annual festival when the temple chariot is brought around the streets near the temple. It is one of the ''[[Pancha Sabhai]]'' temples, the five royal courts of [[Nataraja]] (the dancing form of Shiva),{{sfn|Kumar| 2001| p= 184}} where he performed a cosmic dance.{{sfn|Smith| 1996| pp= 10\u201348}} The Nataraja shrine in the temple represents copper, and features many copper sculptures. Tirunelveli has its fair share of temples, dating back to ancient times. It also prides itself as being the site where the Nellaiappar Temple is located{{sfn|Ayyar| 1991| pp=498\u2013499}}\n\nTirunelveli is also known for [[halwa]], a sweet made of wheat, sugar and ghee. It originated during the mid-1800s at Lakshmi Vilas Stores, which still exist. The art of sweet-making spread to other parts of Tamil Nadu, such as [[Nagercoil]], [[Srivilliputhur]] and [[Thoothukudi]].{{sfn|''The Hindu''|23 June 2012}} Tirunelveli halwa was popularised by Irutukadai Halwa, a shop opened in 1900 which sells the sweets only during twilight.{{sfn|''The Hindu''|21 April 2011}}\n\n[[File:CentralTheatreTvli.jpg|200px|thumb|right| Central Theatre, Tirunelveli]]\nTirunelveli has a number of cinemas which predominantly play Tamil movies. It is among the 40 cities in India with FM radio stations. Tirunelveli's stations are Tirunelveli Vanoli Nilayam ([[All India Radio]], from the Government of India), Suryan FM (operated by Sun Network on 93.5&nbsp;MHz) and Hello FM (operated by the Malai Malar Group on 106.4&nbsp;MHz).{{sfn|''Business Line''|26 February 2003}}\n\nA number of state- and national-level sports events are sponsored in Tirunelveli annually. The VOC grounds (in central Palayamkottai) and the Anna Stadium (on St. Thomas Road) are popular venues in the city, and some events are held at scholastic sports facilities.{{sfn|''The Hindu''|10 January 2007}} As in India generally, the most popular sport is [[cricket]]. Also popular are football, volleyball, swimming and hockey, played on facilities provided by the Tirunelveli Division of the Sports Development Authority of Tamil Nadu.{{sfn|Sports Development Authority}}\n\nThe Government Exhibition, an annual event at Exhibition Grounds, attracts thousands of visitors from in and around Tirunelveli.{{sfn|''The Hindu''|24 June 2012}} the [[District Science Center - Tirunelveli]] is in the centre of the city. Near the city are regional tourist attractions such as the Manimuthar and Papanasam Dams, the Ariakulam and Koonthakulam Bird Sanctuaries, Manjolai and Upper Kodaiyar.{{sfn|Tourism in Tirunelveli}}\n\n==Education==\n[[File:Tirunelveli Medical College2.JPG|thumb|left|Tirunelveli Medical College auditorium|alt=a building viewed amidst trees]]\nDuring the 1790s, Tamil Christians established a number of schools in Tirunelveli.{{sfn| Lewis|2004|p=117}} The missionary educational system included primary and boarding schools, seminaries, industrial schools, orphanages and colleges. {{sfn|O'Connor|2000|p=285}} The first boarding school for girls was opened in 1821, but its efforts were hampered by the emphasis on Christian education.{{sfn|Forbes|1996|p=39}}{{sfn| Manohar|2007|p=2}} [[Sir Thomas Munro, 1st Baronet|Thomas Munro]] (1761&nbsp;\u2013 1827 CE) of the British East India Company established a two-tier school system: district schools, teaching law, and sub-district schools teaching vernacular languages in the [[Madras Presidency]]. Tirunelveli had four sub-district schools: two teaching Tamil and one each for Telugu and Persian.{{sfn|Raman|2012|pp=102\u2013103}} \n\nTirunelveli city has 80 schools: 29 higher secondary schools, 12 high schools, 22 middle schools and 17 primary schools; the city corporation operates 33 of these schools. The city has eight arts and science colleges and six professional colleges. The [[Manonmaniam Sundaranar University]] is named for poet Manonmaniam Sundaranar, who wrote ''\"Tamil Thai Vazhthu\"'' the state anthem.{{sfn|Urban Infrastructure report|2007|p=21}} Most Christian schools and colleges in the city are located in the Palayamkottai area.{{sfn| Ramchandani|2000|p=144}}\n\n[[Anna University of Technology Tirunelveli]] was established in 2007, offering a variety of engineering and technology courses for undergraduate and graduate students. [[Tirunelveli Medical College]],{{sfn|Nellai Medical College}} Veterinary College and Research Institution{{sfn|Veterinary College}} and the [[Government College of Engineering, Tirunelveli]]{{sfn|Government College of Engineering, Tirunelveli}} are professional colleges operated by the government of Tamil Nadu. The Jesuit St. Xavier's College, and St. John's College (operated by the [[Church of South India]] diocese), MDT Hindu College, Sadakathulla Appa College and [[Sarah Tucker College]] are notable arts colleges.\n\nThe Indian Institute of Geomagnetism (IIG) operates a regional unit, the Equatorial Geophysical Research Laboratory, conducting research in geomagnetism and atmospheric and space sciences.{{sfn|Equatorial Geophysical Research Laboratory, Tirunelveli (T.N)}} The city has a District Science Centre (a satellite unit of [[Visvesvaraya Industrial and Technological Museum]], [[Bangalore]]) with permanent exhibitions, science shows, interactive self-guided tours, a mini-planetarium and sky observation.{{sfn| Visvesvaraya Satellite Centre}}{{sfn|''The Hindu''|17 January 2007}}\n\nTirunelveli and the district have a high rate of child labour.{{sfn| Kapadia|2002|p=111}} The drop in female school attendance between ages 15 and 19 is almost four times greater than that in the rest of Tamil Nadu.{{sfn| Kapadia|2002|p=75}}\n\n=={{anchor|Utility services}}Utilities==\nElectric service to Tirunelveli is regulated and distributed by the [[Tamil Nadu Electricity Board]] (TNEB).{{sfn|Important Address of TNEB}} The city is headquarters for the Tirunelveli region of the four-division TNEB and, with its suburbs, forms the Tirunelveli Electricity Distribution Circle.{{sfn|Important Address of TNEB}} A chief distribution engineer is stationed at regional headquarters.{{sfn|Important Address of TNEB}} Water supply is provided by the [[Tirunelveli Municipal Corporation|Tirunelveli City Corporation]] from the Tamirabarani River, throughout the city.{{sfn|Urban Infrastructure report|2007|p=17}}{{sfn|Water Supply Details}}\n\nAbout 100 metric tonnes of solid waste are collected from the city daily in door-to-door collection; source segregation and disposal is performed by the sanitary department of the Tirunelveli Municipal Corporation.{{sfn|Waste management programme|2011}} The underground drainage system was constituted in 1998, covering 22 percent of the corporation area. The remaining system for disposal of sewage is through septic tanks and public conveniences.{{sfn|Urban Infrastructure report|2007|p=18}}{{sfn|Tirunelveli sewarage|2011}} The corporation maintains a total of {{convert|184.8|km|mi}} of stormwater drains, 27 percent of the total road length. The clinics operated by the corporation provide primary health care to the urban poor through family-welfare and immunisation programs.{{sfn|Urban Infrastructure report|2007|p=21}} In addition, there are private hospitals and clinics providing health care to citizens.{{sfn|Tirunelveli hospitals|2011}}\n\nTirunelveli is part of the Tirunelveli Telecom District of [[Bharat Sanchar Nigam Limited]] (BSNL), India's state-owned telecom and internet-services provider. Both Global System for Mobile Communications ([[GSM]]) and [[Code division multiple access]] (CDMA) mobile services are available. In addition to telecommunications, BSNL also provides [[broadband internet]] service.{{sfn|List of cities where BSNL broadband service is available (As on 1 January 2007)}} Tirunelveli is one of a few cities in India where BSNL's Caller Line Identification (CLI)-based internet service, Netone, is available.{{sfn|List of cities where Calling Line Identification (CLI) Based Internet Service is available}} The city has a Passport Seva Kendra, a public-private-sector collaboration, which accepts passport applications from the Tirunelveli region for the passport office in Madurai.{{sfn|''The Hindu''|8 December 2012}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|19em}}\n\n==References==\n{{refbegin|3}}\n* {{cite report |url=http://www.tn.gov.in/cma/CDP/Corporations/Tirunelveli.pdf|format=PDF |title=Conversion of City Corporate Plan into Business Plan |last=Urban Infrastructure report |publisher=Tamil Nadu Urban Infrastructure Financial Services Limited |year=2007  |accessdate=29 December 2012|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book |last=Ayyar |first=P. V. Jagadisa |title=South Indian shrines: illustrated |year=1991 |publisher=Asian Educational Services |location=New Delhi |isbn=81-206-0151-3|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NLSGFW1uZboC&pg=PA498&dq=tinnevelly+ayyar&hl=en&sa=X&ei=0YrWUPCJMofA9QTw7YCQAQ&ved=0CDMQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=tinnevelly%20ayyar&f=false|ref=harv}}.\n* {{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zjTneAGmatsC |title=Th