0|accessdate=16 April 2011|format=PDF|ref={{sfnRef|Key highlights of the general elections 1977 to the Sixth Lok Sabha}}}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://eci.nic.in/eci_main/StatisticalReports/LS_1980/Vol_I_LS_80.pdf|title=Key highlights of the general elections 1980 to the Seventh Lok Sabha|publisher=Election Commission of India|page=79|accessdate=26 June 2012|format=PDF|ref={{sfnRef|Key highlights of the general elections 1980 to the Seventh Lok Sabha}}}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://eci.nic.in/eci_main/SR_KeyHighLights/LS_1984/Vol_I_LS_84.pdf|title=Key highlights of the general elections 1984 to the Eighth Lok Sabha|publisher=Election Commission of India|page=73|accessdate=16 April 2011|format=PDF|ref={{sfnRef|Key highlights of the general elections 1984 to the Eighth Lok Sabha|publisher=Election Commission of India}}}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://eci.nic.in/eci_main/SR_KeyHighLights/LS_1989/Vol_I_LS_89.pdf|title=Key highlights of the general elections 1989 to the Ninth Lok Sabha|publisher=Election Commission of India|page=81|accessdate=16 April 2011|format=PDF|ref={{sfnRef|Key highlights of the general elections 1989 to the Ninth Lok Sabha}}}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://eci.nic.in/eci_main/SR_KeyHighLights/LS_1991/VOL_I_LS_91.pdf|title=Key highlights of the general elections 1991 to the Tenth Lok Sabha|publisher=Election Commission of India|page=51|accessdate=16 April 2011|format=PDF|ref={{sfnRef|Key highlights of the general elections 1991 to the Tenth Lok Sabha}}}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://eci.nic.in/eci_main/StatisticalReports/LS_1996/Vol_I_LS_96.pdf|title=Key highlights of the general elections 1996 to the Eleventh Lok Sabha|publisher=Election Commission of India|page=86|accessdate=26 June 2012|format=PDF|ref={{sfnRef|Key highlights of the general elections 1996 to the Eleventh Lok Sabha}}}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://eci.nic.in/eci_main/SR_KeyHighLights/LS_1998/Vol_I_LS_98.pdf|title=Key highlights of the general elections 1998 to the Twelfth Lok Sabha|publisher=Election Commission of India|page=85|accessdate=16 April 2011|format=PDF|ref={{sfnRef|Key highlights of the general elections 1998 to the Twelfth Lok Sabha}}}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://eci.nic.in/eci_main/SR_KeyHighLights/LS_1999/Vol_I_LS_99.pdf|title=Key highlights of the general elections 1999 to the Thirteenth Lok Sabha|publisher=Election Commission of India|page=85|accessdate=16 April 2011|format=PDF|ref={{sfnRef|Key highlights of the general elections 1999 to the Thirteenth Lok Sabha}}}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://eci.nic.in/eci_main/SR_KeyHighLights/LS_2004/Vol_I_LS_2004.pdf|title=Key highlights of the general elections 2004 to the Fourteenth Lok Sabha|publisher=Election Commission of India|page=94|accessdate=16 April 2011|format=PDF|ref={{sfnRef|Key highlights of the general elections 2004 to the Fourteenth Lok Sabha}}}}\n* {{cite web|title=Tirunelveli sewarage|url=http://tirunelvelicorp.tn.gov.in/sewerage.html|publisher=Tirunelveli Corporation|accessdate = 26 June 2012|year=2011|ref={{sfnRef|Tirunelveli sewarage|2011}}}}\n* {{cite web|title=Waste management programme|url=http://tirunelvelicorp.tn.gov.in/waste.html|publisher=Tirunelveli Corporation|accessdate = 26 June 2012|year=2011|ref={{sfnRef|Waste management programme|2011}}}}\n* {{cite web|title=Tirunelveli district police|url=http://www.nellai.tn.nic.in/rti_pdf/rti_pol.pdf|publisher=Tamil Nadu Police|year=2011|pages=1\u20132|accessdate = 26 June 2012|format=PDF|ref={{sfnRef|Tirunelveli district police|2011}} }}\n* {{cite web|title=Chairman of Tirunelveli|url=http://tirunelvelicorp.tn.gov.in/mayor.html|publisher=Tirunelveli Municipality, Government of Tamil Nadu|year=2011|accessdate = 26 June 2012|ref={{sfnRef|Tirunelveli Municipality chairman|2011}} }}\n* {{cite web|title=Vice Chairman of Tirunelveli|url=http://tirunelvelicorp.tn.gov.in/deputymayor.html|publisher=Tirunelveli Municipality, Government of Tamil Nadu|year=2011|accessdate = 26 June 2012|ref={{sfnRef|Tirunelveli Municipality vice-chairman|2011}} }}\n* {{cite web|title=List of Councillors of Tirunelveli|url=http://tirunelvelicorp.tn.gov.in/councilors2011.html|publisher=Tirunelveli Corporation|year=2011|accessdate = 26 June 2012|ref={{sfnRef|List of Councillors|2011}} }}\n* {{cite web|title=Commissioner of Tirunelveli|url=http://tirunelvelicorp.tn.gov.in/commissioner.html|publisher=Tirunelveli Municipality, Government of Tamil Nadu|year=2011|accessdate = 26 June 2012|ref={{sfnRef|Tirunelveli Municipality Commissioner|2011}} }}\n* {{cite web|title=MLA of Tirunelveli|url=http://www.assembly.tn.gov.in/members/profile/224.html|publisher=Government of Tamil Nadu|year=2011|accessdate = 26 June 2012|ref={{sfnRef|MLA of Tirunelveli|2011}} }}\n* {{cite web|title=Members of Lok Sabha from Tamil Nadu|url=http://www.tn.gov.in/government/loksaba?page=1|publisher=Government of Tamil Nadu|year=2014|accessdate =26 May 2014|ref={{sfnRef|MP of Tirunelveli|2014}} }}\n* {{cite web\n| url = http://www.assembly.tn.gov.in/Const_map/map.htm\n| title = List of Assembly Constituencies\n| year=2010\n| accessdate = 30 June 2012\n| work = Tamil Nadu\n| publisher = Tamil Nadu state government\n|ref={{sfnRef|List of Assembly constituencies|2010}}\n }}\n* {{cite journal|title=Economic and political weekly, Volume 30|url=http://www.epw.in/epw-archive.html|page=2396|publisher=Sameeksha Trust|accessdate = 8 June 2012|year=1995|ref={{sfnRef|Economic and political weekly|1995}} }}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikivoyage|Tirunelveli}}\n{{Commons category}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080110191554/http://tirunelvelicorp.tn.gov.in/ Tirunelveli City-Municipal Corporation]\n\n{{Tirunelveli district}}\n{{Municipalities of Tamil Nadu}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Tirunelveli| ]]\n[[Category:Cities and towns in Tirunelveli district]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-protected|small=yes}}\n{{About|the municipal corporation in Tamil Nadu, India|its namesake district|Tirunelveli district}}\n{{for|the town in Sri Lanka|Thirunelveli, Sri Lanka}} \n{{good article}}\n\n{{Use Indian English|date=June 2016}} \n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2013}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                            = Tirunelveli\n| official_name                   = \n| native_name                     = \u0ba4\u0bbf\u0bb0\u0bc1\u0ba8\u0bc6\u0bb2\u0bcd\u0bb5\u0bc7\u0bb2\u0bbf\n| other_name                      = Nellai(shorter version), Tinnevelly(version used during the British Raj)\n| settlement_type                 = [[Metropolis]]\n| image_skyline                   = Tirunelveli_city.jpg\n| image_alt                       = \n| image_caption                   = Clockwise from Top Left : [[Nellaiappar Temple|Swami Nellaiappar Temple]], [[Tirunelveli Junction railway station|Tirunelveli Junction Railway Station]], Thiruvalluvar Bridge - Aerial view, Town Arch, Speaker Chellapandian Flyover near Vannarapettai at night, Tirunelveli City Skyline, Older side of Sulochana Mudaliar Bridge at night across river Thamirabharani connecting Downtown Tirunelveli and Kokkirakulam, [[National Highway 44 (India)|NH 44]] cutting through the Reddiyarpatti Hillock, [[Thamirabarani River]] passing between Downtown Tirunelveli and Kokkirakulam, [[Tirunelveli Municipal Corporation|Tirunelveli City Municipal Corporation Building]]\n| nickname                        = The Oxford of South India\n| map_alt                         = \n| map_caption                     = \n| pushpin_map                     = India Tamil Nadu#India\n| pushpin_label_position          = right\n| pushpin_map_alt                 = \n| pushpin_map_caption             = \n| coordinates                     = {{Coord|8|43|41.82|N|77|41|43.94|E|region:IN|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type                = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n| subdivision_name                = [[India]]\n| subdivision_type1               = [[States and territories of India|State]]\n| subdivision_name1               = [[Tamil Nadu]]\n| subdivision_type2               = [[List of regions of India|Region]]\n| subdivision_name2               = [[Pandya Nadu]]\n| subdivision_type3               = [[List of districts of India|District]]\n| subdivision_name3               = [[Tirunelveli District]]\n| established_title               = <!-- Established -->\n| established_date                = \n| founder                         = \n| named_for                       = [[Shiva|Lord Shiva]] of the city's famous [[Nellaiappar Temple|Arulmigu Nellaiappar Temple]]\n| government_type                 = [[Municipal Corporation]]\n| governing_body                  = [[Tirunelveli City Municipal Corporation]]\n| leader_title                    = Mayor\n| leader_name                     = \"Vacant\"\n| parts_style                     = para\n| parts                           = Tirunelveli Town<br/>[[Palayamkottai]]<br/>[[Melapalayam]]<br/>[[Pettai, Tirunelveli|Pettai]], [[Thachanallur]]\n| unit_pref                       = Metric\n| area_footnotes                  = \n| area_total_km2                  = 189.9\n| area_rank                       = 5\n| elevation_footnotes             = \n| elevation_m                     = 47\n| population_total                = 473637\n| population_as_of                = 2011\n| population_footnotes            = <ref name=population>{{cite web|title=Census 2011|url=http://www.censusindia.gov.in/pca/SearchDetails.aspx?Id=701597|publisher=The Registrar General & Census Commissioner, India|accessdate=29 May 2016}}</ref>\n| population_density_km2          = 4370\n| population_metro                = 497826\n| population_rank                 = 7th in Tamil Nadu, 98th in India\n| population_demonym              = Tirunelvelian, Tirunelveli Karan, Nellaian, and Nellaikaran\n| demographics_type1              = Languages\n| demographics1_title1            = Official\n| demographics1_info1             = [[Tamil language|Tamil]]\n| timezone1                       = [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n| utc_offset1                     = +5:30\n| postal_code_type                = [[Postal Index Number|Pin Codes]]\n| postal_code                     = 627001, 627002, 627003, 627004, 627005, 627006, 627007, 627008, 627009, 627010, 627011, 627012, 627353, 627357, 627358\n| area_code                       = [[Telephone numbers in India#Fixed (landline) numbers|91 (0)462, (0)4633]]\n| area_code_type                  = Telephone code\n| registration_plate              = TN-72(City Area), TN-72A(Valliyur Region), TN-76A(Ambasamudram Region)\n| website                         = http://www.tirunelvelicorporation.in/\n| website developer               = \n| mail id                         = \n}}\n[[File:Tiruneveli .jpg|thumb|Tirunelveli City Municipal Corporation Building named after V O Chidambaranar]]'''Tirunelveli''' {{audio|Tirunelveli-pronunciation.ogg|pronunciation}}, also known as '''Nellai''' and historically (during [[British Raj|British rule]]) as '''Tinnevelly''', is a major city in the [[India]]n state of [[Tamil Nadu]]. It is the administrative headquarters of the [[Tirunelveli District]]. It is the sixth-largest municipal corporation in the state after [[Chennai]], [[Coimbatore]], [[Madurai]], [[Trichy]] and [[Salem, Tamil Nadu|Salem]]. Tirunelveli is located {{convert|700|km|mi|abbr=on}} southwest of the state capital [[Chennai]], {{convert|58|km|mi|abbr=on}} away from [[Thoothukudi]] and {{convert|73|km|mi|abbr=on}} from [[Kanyakumari]]. The downtown is located on the west bank of the [[Thamirabarani River]]; its twin [[Palayankottai|Palayamkottai]] is on the east bank. [[Palayamkottai]] is called as the Oxford of the south India. It is a hub of many schools, colleges and many important government offices. \n\nTirunelveli is an ancient city, and is more than 2000 years old. Tirunelveli is believed to be an ancient settlement of great importance. It has been ruled at different times by the [[Early Pandyan Kingdom|Early Pandyas]], the [[Medieval Cholas|Medieval]] and [[Later Cholas]], the later [[Pandyan dynasty|Pandyas]], the [[Madurai Sultanate|Ma'bar]] , the [[Vijayanagar Empire]], the [[Madurai Nayaks]], [[Chanda Sahib]], the [[Carnatic region|Karnatic]] [[Nawab of the Carnatic|kingdom]] and the [[British Raj|British]]. The [[Polygar War]], involving [[Palaiyakkarar]]s led by [[Veerapandiya Kattabomman]] and forces of the British East India Company, was waged on the city's outskirts from 1797 to 1801. \n\nTirunelveli is administered by a [[Tirunelveli Municipal Corporation|Municipal Corporation]], established on 1 June 1994 by the [[Municipal Corporations Act|Municipal Corporation Act]]. The city covers an area of {{convert|189.9|sqkm|sqmi|abbr=on}}, and had a population of 473,637 in 2011 excluding some Municipal corporation region then.The total population after expansion is 968,984. Tirunelveli is well-connected by road and rail with the rest of Tamil Nadu and India. The nearest domestic airport is [[Tuticorin Airport|Thoothukudi Airport]]. The Nearest International Airports are [[Madurai International Airport]] and [[Trivandrum International Airport|Thiruvananthapuram International Airport]]. The nearest Seaport is [[Tuticorin Port Trust|Thoothukudi Port]].\n\nIndustries in Tirunelveli include administrative services, agricultural trading, tourism, banking, agricultural machinery, information technology and educational services. The city is an educational hub of southern India, with institutions such as Anna University Regional Campus - Tirunelveli, [[Tirunelveli Medical College]], The Tirunelveli Veterinary College and Research Institution, [[Government Law College, Tirunelveli|Tirunelveli Law College]],  the [[ Government College of Engineering, Tirunelveli|Government College of Engineering]], [[Manonmaniam Sundaranar University]] and much more. \n\nTirunelveli has a number of historical monuments, the [[Nellaiappar Temple|Swami Nellaiappar Temple]] being the most prominent.\n\n==Etymology==\nTirunelveli is one of the many temple towns in the state which is named after the grooves, clusters or forests dominated by a particular variety of a tree or shrub and the same variety of tree or shrub sheltering the presiding deity. The region is believed to have been covered with Venu forest and hence called Venuvanam.{{sf|Reddy| 2013| p= 10}} Tirunelveli was known in [[Sambandar]]'s seventh-century Saiva canonical work ''[[Tevaram]]'' as Thirunelveli.{{sfn|Moondram Thirumurai}} Swami Nellaiappar temple inscriptions say that [[Shiva]] (as Vrihivritesvara) descended in the form of a hedge and roof to save the paddy crop of a devotee. In Hindu legend, the place was known as Venuvana (\"forest of bamboo\") due to the presence of bamboo in the temple under which the deity is believed to have appeared.{{sfn|Ayyar| 1991| pp=498\u2013499}} The early Pandyas named the city Thenpandya Nadu or Thenpandya Seemai, the Cholas Mudikonda Cholamandalam and the Nayaks Tirunelveli Seemai; it was known as Tinnelvelly by the British, and Tirunelveli after independence.{{sfn|Kanmony|2010|p=42}}{{sfn|Caldwell|1989|p=88}} The word ''Tirunelveli'' is derived from three Tamil words: ''thiru'', ''nel'' and ''veli'', meaning \"sacred paddy hedge\".{{sfn|P.|2008|p=67}}{{sfn|Caldwell|1989|p=88}}\n\n==History==\n[[File:Nellaiappar temple pillar.JPG|250x250px|left|thumb|Sculpted pillar in Nellaiappar Temple (the largest temple in Tirunelveli)|alt=granite column with sculpture showing a person with a bow]]\nThe history of Tirunelveli was researched by [[Robert Caldwell]] (1814\u201391), a Christian [[missionary]] who visited the area.{{sfn|Caldwell|1989}}{{sfn|Daughrity|2005}}{{sfn|Mission Studies|2007}} Tirunelveli was under the rule of [[Pandian Empire|Pandya]] kings as their secondary capital; [[Madurai]] was the empire's primary capital.{{sfn| Stein|Johnson|Bayly|Richards|1989|p=79}} The Pandya dynasty in the region dates to several centuries before the [[Christian era]] from inscriptions by [[Asoka the great|Ashoka]] (304\u2013232 BCE) and mention in the ''[[Mahavamsa]]'', the ''[[Brihat-Samhita]]'' and the writings of [[Megasthenes]] (350\u2013290 CE). The province came under the rule of [[Cholas]] under [[Rajendra Chola I]] in 1064 CE; however, it is unclear whether he conquered the region or obtained it voluntarily.{{sfn|Caldwell|1989|p=23-30}} Tirunelveli remained under control of the Cholas until the early 13th century, when the second Pandyan empire was established with Madurai as its capital.{{sfn|Salma Ahmed|2011|p=26}}\n\nThe Nellaiappar temple was the royal shrine of the later Pandyas during the 13th and 14th centuries, and the city benefited from dams constructed with royal patronage during the period. After the death of [[Maravarman Kulasekara Pandyan I|Kulasekara Pandian]] (1268\u20131308), the region was occupied by Vijayangara rulers and Marava chieftains (palayakarars, or ''poligars'') during the 16th century. The Maravars occupied the western foothills and the Telugas, and the Kannadigas settled in the black-soil-rich eastern portion. Tirunelveli was the subsidiary capital of the [[Madurai Nayaks]];{{sfn| Stein|Johnson|Bayly|Richards|1989|p=79}} under [[Viswanatha Nayak]] (1529\u201364), the city was rebuilt about 1560. Inscriptions from the Nellaiappar temple indicate generous contributions to the temple.{{sfn|Hunter|1908|pp=379\u2013380}} Nayak rule ended in 1736. \n\nThe region was captured by the subjects of the Mughal Empire such as [[Chanda Sahib]] (1740\u20131754) who declared himself \"Nawab of Tinnevelly\" as well as the [[Nawab of the Carnatic]].\nIn 1743 Nizam-ul-mulk, lieutenant of the [[Deccan Plateau]], displaced most of the Marathas from the region and Tirunelveli came under the rule of the [[Nawabs of Arcot]]. The original power lay in the hands of the ''polygars'', who were originally military chiefs of the Nayaks. The city was the chief commercial town during the Nawab and [[Nayak (ethnic group)|Nayak]] era. The city was known as Nellai Cheemai, with ''Cheemai'' meaning \"a developed foreign town\".{{sfn|''The Hindu''|19 May 2007}}  The ''polygars'' built forts in the hills, had 30,000 troops and waged war among themselves. In 1755, the British government sent a mission under Major Heron and Mahfuz Khan which restored some order and bestowed the city to Mahfuz Khan. The ''poligars'' waged war against Mahfuz Khan seven miles from Tirunelveli, but were defeated. The failure of Mahfuz Khan led the East India Company to send Muhammed Yusuf for help. Khan became ruler, rebelled in 1763 and was hanged in 1764. In 1758, British troops under Colonel Fullarton reduced the ''polygar'' stronghold under [[Veerapandiya Kattabomman]]. In 1797, the first Polygar war broke out between the British (under Major Bannerman) and the ''polygars'' (headed by Kattabomman). Some ''polygars'' (such as the head of Ettaiyapuram) aided the British; Kattabomman was defeated and hanged in his home province of Panchalaguruchi. Two years later, another rebellion became known as the Second Polygar War. Panchalankuruchi fell to the British, after stiff resistance. The [[Carnatic region]] came under British rule following a treaty with the Nawab of Carnatic.{{sfn|Hunter|1908|pp=375\u2013379}}{{sfn|Caldwell|1989|p=93-96}}{{sfn|W.|2002|p=214-221}}\n\nAfter acquiring Tirunelveli from the Nawab of Arcot in 1801, the British anglicised its name to \"Tinnevelly\" and made it the headquarters of Tinnelvelli District. The administrative and military headquarters was located in Palayamkottai (anglicised as \"Palankottah\"), from which attacks against the ''polygars'' were launched. After independence both cities reverted to their original names, and Tirunelveli remained the capital of Tirunelveli district. A separate [[Thoothukudi district]] was split off in 1986.{{sfn|Kanmony|2010|p=42}}\nIn 2019 , [[Tenkasi]] was split from [[Tirunelveli District]] forming [[Tenkasi district|Tenkasi District]].\n\n==Geography and climate==\n\nTirunelveli has the relatively rare dry-summer [[Tropical climate|Tropical savannah climate]] (K\u00f6ppen: ''As''), scattered irregularly across the world but is relatively common in areas near the Laccadive Sea.\n\n[[File:Agasthiyamalai range and Tirunelveli rainshadow.jpg|thumb|The [[Agasthiyamalai]] hills cut off Tirunelveli from the [[southwest monsoon]], creating a [[rainshadow]] region.|alt=image of hills with dark skyline]]\nTirunelveli is located at {{Coord|8|43|41.82|N|77|41|43.94|E|region:IN|display=inline}},{{sfn|Falling Rain Genomics}} and its average elevation is {{convert|47|m|ft}}. It is located at the southernmost tip of the Deccan plateau. The Tamirabarani River divides the city into the Tirunelveli quarter and the Palayamkottai area. The river (with its tributaries, such as the Chittar) is the major source of irrigation, and is fed by the northeast and southwest monsoons.{{sfn|Hunter|1908|p=215}} The major lakes in the city are Nainar Lake and Udayarpetti Lake. The area around the Tamirabarani River and the Chittar has five streams: Kodagan, Palayan, Tirunelveli, Marudur East and Marudur West, and the Chittar feeds fifteen other channels. The soil is friable, red and sandy.{{sfn|Hunter|1908|pp=379\u2013380}}\n \nThe climate of Tirunelveli is generally hot and humid. The average temperature during summer (March to June) ranges from {{convert|25|\u00b0C|\u00b0F}} to {{convert|41|\u00b0C|\u00b0F}}, and {{convert|18|\u00b0C|\u00b0F}} to {{convert|29|\u00b0C|\u00b0F}} during the rest of the year. The average annual rainfall is {{convert|680|mm|in}}. Maximum precipitation occurs during the [[northeast monsoon]] (October\u2013December). Since the economy of the district is primarily based on agriculture, flooding of the Tamarabarani River or a fluctuation in monsoon rain has an immediate impact on the local economy. The primary crops grown in the region are paddy and cotton. Pineapples were introduced during the 16th century, [[Chili pepper|chilly]] and tobacco during the late 16th and potatoes during the early 17th centuries.{{sfn| Subrahmanyam|1990|p=28}} The most common tree is the [[Borassus|palmyra palm]], a raw material in cottage industries. Other trees grown in the region are [[teak]], wild jack, ''manjakadambu'', ''venteak'', ''vengai'', ''pillaimaruthu'', ''karimaruthu'' and bamboo. Livestock of the city and district comprises cattle, buffalo, goats, sheep and other animals in smaller numbers.{{sfn|Soundarapandian|2002| p=48}}\n\n{{Weather box\n|location = Tirunelveli (located in [[Palayamkottai]]) 1981\u20132010, extremes 1947\u20132012\n| metric first = Yes\n| single line = Yes\n| Jan record high C = 36.0\n| Feb record high C = 39.0\n| Mar record high C = 41.7\n| Apr record high C = 42.0\n| May record high C = 42.8\n| Jun record high C = 44.9\n| Jul record high C = 41.9\n| Aug record high C = 39.5\n| Sep record high C = 40.5\n| Oct record high C = 41.0\n| Nov record high C = 38.9\n| Dec record high C = 37.0\n| year record high C = 44.9\n| Jan high C = 31.4\n| Feb high C = 33.5\n| Mar high C = 35.5\n| Apr high C = 36.7\n| May high C = 37.7\n| Jun high C = 36.1\n| Jul high C = 35.2\n| Aug high C = 35.2\n| Sep high C = 35.8\n| Oct high C = 34.0\n| Nov high C = 31.3\n| Dec high C = 30.5\n| year high C = 34.4\n| Jan low C = 22.4\n| Feb low C = 23.0\n| Mar low C = 24.3\n| Apr low C = 25.9\n| May low C = 26.7\n| Jun low C = 26.7\n| Jul low C = 26.4\n| Aug low C = 26.2\n| Sep low C = 25.8\n| Oct low C = 24.8\n| Nov low C = 23.7\n| Dec low C = 22.8\n| year low C = 24.9\n| Jan record low C = 18.0\n| Feb record low C = 18.0\n| Mar record low C = 18.4\n| Apr record low C = 20.3\n| May record low C = 16.3\n| Jun record low C = 20.4\n| Jul record low C = 19.3\n| Aug record low C = 21.6\n| Sep record low C = 19.5\n| Oct record low C = 17.9\n| Nov record low C = 16.9\n| Dec record low C = 17.6\n| year record low C = 16.9\n| rain colour = green\n| Jan rain mm = 24.5\n| Feb rain mm = 26.0\n| Mar rain mm = 44.0\n| Apr rain mm = 59.5\n| May rain mm = 52.2\n| Jun rain mm = 6.6\n| Jul rain mm = 